---

<Base title={title} description={description} jsonLd={jsonLd}>

  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="lj-hero">
    <div class="lj-hero__overlay"></div>
    <div class="lj-hero__content">
      <p class="lj-hero__eyebrow">Lux Jewels, Since 2007</p>
      <h1>Engagement Rings Canada</h1>
      <div class="lj-hero__ctas">
        <a href="https://luxjewels.com/booking-appointment/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="lj-hero-btn-primary">Book Free Consultation</a>
        <a href="https://stan.store/luxjewels" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="lj-hero-btn-secondary">No-BS Call - $199</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- BREADCRUMB -->
  <div style="background:#f9f8f6;border-bottom:1px solid #e6e2de;">
    <div class="lj-container">
      <nav class="lj-breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <span>Home</span>
      </nav>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- INTRO + QUICK ANSWER -->
  <section class="lj-section lj-section-pad" style="background:#ffffff;">
    <div class="lj-container">
      <div class="lj-container--narrow" style="margin:0 auto;padding:0;">

        <div class="lj-prose">
          <p>I don't pressure you into a stone you can't afford. I don't hide prices behind a "contact us" button, and I don't pretend a bigger budget automatically means a better ring. I'm Suman Smith, and I've spent over 20 years helping couples across Canada and the US find the engagement ring that actually fits their life, not a showroom floor target. I started Lux Jewels in 2007, and in 2015 I became the first Canadian jeweller to specialize exclusively in lab-grown diamonds. I do things differently because I've seen too many buyers overpay for a name, not a stone.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="lj-quick-answer">
          <p>Lux Jewels designs custom lab-grown engagement rings for couples across Canada. Stones are IGI-certified, set in 14K or 18K repurposed gold or platinum 950, and delivered via FedEx Priority insured shipping. Custom design takes 4&ndash;6 weeks. You can start with a free 30-minute video consultation or book a No-BS Call for direct, one-on-one advice.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="lj-prose">
          <ul>
            <li>IGI-certified lab-grown diamonds and moissanite</li>
            <li>Custom design from concept to finished ring</li>
            <li>Canada-wide and US delivery via FedEx Priority, insured</li>
            <li>4&ndash;6 weeks from design approval to delivery</li>
            <li>14K, 18K repurposed gold (99.5% previously refined) and platinum 950</li>
            <li>Free 30&ndash;40 min video consultation included</li>
            <li>First Canadian lab-grown specialist since 2015</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WHY LAB-GROWN -->
  <section class="lj-section lj-section-pad" style="background:#f9f8f6;">
    <div class="lj-container">
      <div class="lj-container--narrow" style="margin:0 auto;padding:0;">
        <div class="lj-prose">
          <h2>Why Canadians Are Choosing Lab-Grown Engagement Rings in 2026</h2>
          <p>The market has shifted. Five years ago, lab-grown diamonds were a niche choice. Today they're what a lot of couples in Canada actively look for, and the reason's simple: you can get a visually identical, chemically identical stone for 60&ndash;85% less than mined.</p>
          <p>A 1-carat G, VS1, excellent-cut mined diamond in Canada runs CA$6,000&ndash;CA$9,000 or more from a national chain. The same grade lab-grown stone? CA$800&ndash;CA$2,200 depending on where you buy. That's not a compromise. That's a smarter allocation of the same budget.</p>
          <p>Lab-grown diamonds are real diamonds. The only difference is origin. A mined diamond forms under the earth over billions of years. A lab-grown diamond forms in a controlled environment over weeks, using either HPHT (high pressure, high temperature) or CVD (chemical vapour deposition). The result is the same crystal structure, the same Mohs hardness of 10, the same optical properties, and the same 4Cs grading system applies. IGI grades lab-grown diamonds with the same rigour it applies to mined stones.</p>
          <p>Moissanite is a different stone entirely, made from silicon carbide, with a Mohs hardness of 9.25 and a refractive index higher than diamond. It produces more brilliance and more colour fire than a diamond. It's not a diamond substitute; it's a different stone with different optical properties and a different story. I'll help you decide which one fits what you're looking for.</p>
          <p>If you're comparing affordable engagement rings in Canada, lab-grown gives you the most per dollar of any premium stone. And for couples working with a tighter budget, moissanite puts a stunning custom ring within reach of almost any price point.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- COLLECTION -->
  <section class="lj-section lj-section-pad" style="background:#ffffff;">
    <div class="lj-container">
      <div class="lj-container--narrow" style="margin:0 auto;padding:0;">
        <div class="lj-prose">
          <h2>Shop Our Lab-Grown Engagement Ring Collection</h2>
          <p>Every ring Lux Jewels designs starts from a conversation about what you actually want. I don't hand you a catalogue and hope something fits. But if you're exploring, here's what's in the collection.</p>

          <h3>Oval Engagement Rings</h3>
          <p>Oval diamonds are the most popular shape I work with right now. The elongated shape makes the stone look larger than a round of the same carat weight, which means you get more visual impact per dollar. It's flattering on every hand shape. I set oval stones primarily in solitaire, hidden halo, and east-west configurations.</p>
          <p><a href="/oval-engagement-rings/">Browse oval engagement rings</a></p>

          <h3>Emerald Cut Engagement Rings</h3>
          <p>If you want a ring that looks like it belongs in a vault, emerald cut is it. The long, step-cut facets create a hall-of-mirrors effect that's completely different from any brilliant cut. Clarity matters more with emerald cuts since the stone's transparency shows inclusions more easily. I recommend VS1 or better for this shape.</p>
          <p><a href="/emerald-cut-engagement-rings/">Browse emerald cut engagement rings</a></p>

          <h3>Solitaire Engagement Rings</h3>
          <p>One stone. One metal band. No distractions. Solitaires are timeless for a reason: they put all the focus on the centre stone, which means the stone quality becomes the feature. I work with round, oval, and emerald cut centres in solitaire settings in 14K, 18K repurposed gold, and platinum 950.</p>
          <p><a href="/solitaire-engagement-rings/">Browse solitaire engagement rings</a></p>

          <h3>Halo and Hidden Halo Engagement Rings</h3>
          <p>A halo setting places small accent diamonds around the centre stone, adding perimeter sparkle and making the centre stone appear larger. A hidden halo places those accent stones under the girdle of the centre stone, so they catch light from below without being immediately visible from above. Both styles work well with oval and round centre stones.</p>
          <p><a href="/halo-engagement-rings/">Browse halo engagement rings</a></p>

          <h3>Vintage-Inspired Engagement Rings</h3>
          <p>Milgrain detailing, filigree work, pear-shaped stones in antique settings, and mixed metal bands. If the ring shouldn't look like it came from 2026, vintage-inspired design is what you're looking for. I build these with the same IGI-certified stones I use in all my designs, just in settings that reference 1920s and 1930s ring aesthetics.</p>
          <p><a href="/vintage-engagement-rings/">Browse vintage-inspired engagement rings</a></p>

          <h3>Custom Engagement Ring Design</h3>
          <p>You've got a vision but you don't see it here. That's fine. About 60% of the rings I build are fully custom from the first conversation. We'll talk through the stone shape, the band profile, the metal, the setting style, and any detail elements you want, then I'll build a photorealistic CAD rendering for your approval before any metal gets poured.</p>
          <p><a href="/custom-engagement-rings/">Start your custom design</a></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SHAPES GRID -->
  <section class="lj-section lj-section-pad" style="background:#f9f8f6;">
    <div class="lj-container">
      <h2 style="text-align:center;margin-bottom:2rem;">Browse by Ring Style</h2>
      <div class="lj-shapes-grid">
        <a href="/oval-engagement-rings/" class="lj-shape-card">
          <span class="lj-shape-card__name">Oval</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/emerald-cut-engagement-rings/" class="lj-shape-card">
          <span class="lj-shape-card__name">Emerald Cut</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/cushion-engagement-rings/" class="lj-shape-card">
          <span class="lj-shape-card__name">Cushion</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/pear-engagement-rings/" class="lj-shape-card">
          <span class="lj-shape-card__name">Pear</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/round-engagement-rings/" class="lj-shape-card">
          <span class="lj-shape-card__name">Round</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/halo-engagement-rings/" class="lj-shape-card">
          <span class="lj-shape-card__name">Halo</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/solitaire-engagement-rings/" class="lj-shape-card">
          <span class="lj-shape-card__name">Solitaire</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/vintage-engagement-rings/" class="lj-shape-card">
          <span class="lj-shape-card__name">Vintage</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/custom-engagement-rings/" class="lj-shape-card">
          <span class="lj-shape-card__name">Custom</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WHAT MAKES LUX JEWELS DIFFERENT -->
  <section class="lj-section lj-section-pad" style="background:#ffffff;">
    <div class="lj-container">
      <div class="lj-container--narrow" style="margin:0 auto;padding:0;">
        <div class="lj-prose">
          <h2>What Makes Lux Jewels Different From Other Canadian Jewellers</h2>
          <p>I'll be direct about what separates the way I work from how most jewellers operate.</p>
          <p>First, I show you the grading report. Every lab-grown diamond I source comes with an IGI grading certificate. That certificate has a report number laser-inscribed on the stone's girdle. You can verify the stone yourself. There's no ambiguity about what you're buying. Most retail environments don't walk you through this step.</p>
          <p>Second, I don't have a showroom to rent. I work online, which means every dollar you'd spend on a jewellery district lease goes toward the stone and the craftsmanship instead. Canada-wide delivery via FedEx Priority, insured with signature required, is the model. It works. I've shipped to every province.</p>
          <p>Third, you're talking to the designer. There's no sales associate, no commission pressure, no upsell pipeline. When you book a free consultation with Lux Jewels, you're booking time with me. I've been doing this since 2007. I'm not going to recommend a stone that doesn't serve you.</p>
          <p>Fourth, my pricing is written down. That price table is coming up in the next section. No "call for pricing." No guessing games. The Canadian market has a transparency problem and I've been trying to fix it since 2015 when I committed to lab-grown as the primary offering.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- STONE TYPES -->
  <section class="lj-section lj-section-pad" style="background:#f9f8f6;">
    <div class="lj-container">
      <div class="lj-container--narrow" style="margin:0 auto;padding:0;">
        <div class="lj-prose">
          <h2>IGI-Certified Lab-Grown Diamonds and Moissanite</h2>

          <h3>Lab-Grown Diamonds</h3>
          <p>A lab-grown diamond is a diamond. The Federal Trade Commission in the US clarified this in 2018: the word "diamond" applies to any stone with the same chemical, optical, and physical properties as a mined diamond, regardless of origin. IGI grades lab-grown diamonds using the same 4Cs system as natural diamonds: cut, colour, clarity, and carat weight.</p>
          <p>When I source stones for Lux Jewels customers, I look for E or F colour grades and VS1 clarity for most designs. That combination gives you a stone that's eye-clean with near-colourless to colourless appearance. The difference between E and F is not perceptible in a set ring. The difference between VS1 and SI1, in a step-cut like emerald, absolutely can be.</p>
          <p>Every stone I supply comes with an IGI report. The report number is laser-inscribed on the girdle. You can check it.</p>
          <p><a href="/lab-grown-diamonds-canada/">Learn more about lab-grown diamonds in Canada</a></p>

          <h3>Moissanite</h3>
          <p>Moissanite is not a diamond. I want to be upfront about that. It's a silicon carbide gemstone, first discovered in a meteorite crater in 1893 by Henri Moissan. The gem-quality moissanite used in jewellery today is lab-created by Charles &amp; Colvard, who produce the Forever One line.</p>
          <p>Moissanite has a Mohs hardness of 9.25, which means it's durable enough for everyday wear on an engagement ring. Its refractive index is higher than diamond, which gives it more brilliance and a distinctive rainbow fire that some wearers love and others find too flashy. That's a personal preference, not a quality issue.</p>
          <p>The price difference is significant. A 1-carat moissanite runs CA$250&ndash;CA$600 in a custom design compared to CA$800&ndash;CA$2,200 for a lab-grown diamond of similar size. If budget is the driver, moissanite is the honest recommendation.</p>
          <p><a href="/moissanite-engagement-rings/">Browse moissanite engagement rings</a></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PROCESS -->
  <section class="lj-section lj-section-pad" style="background:#ffffff;">
    <div class="lj-container">
      <div class="lj-container--narrow" style="margin:0 auto;padding:0;">
        <div class="lj-prose">
          <h2>How Our Custom Ring Process Works</h2>
          <p>You don't need to know exactly what you want before you contact me. That's what the consultation is for. Here's how the process goes.</p>

          <h3>Step 1: Free Video Consultation (30&ndash;40 minutes)</h3>
          <p>We talk via Zoom or Google Meet. I'll ask about the style you're drawn to, the metal preferences, the budget, the wearer's lifestyle, and whether you've got any reference images. By the end of this call you'll know which stone type I'd recommend, what carat weight fits your budget, and what setting direction makes sense. <a href="https://luxjewels.com/booking-appointment/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Book your free consultation here.</a></p>

          <h3>Step 2: Design and CAD Rendering</h3>
          <p>I build a photorealistic 3D render of the ring based on our conversation. You'll see exactly what the ring will look like before I source the stone or start casting. We revise until you're happy. This step typically takes 5&ndash;7 business days.</p>

          <h3>Step 3: Stone Sourcing with IGI Report</h3>
          <p>Once the design is locked, I source the stone against your approved specifications. You'll receive the IGI grading report with the report number before any payment is made. If the stone doesn't match the agreed specifications, I source again.</p>

          <h3>Step 4: Casting, Setting, and Delivery</h3>
          <p>Ring casting and stone setting takes 10&ndash;15 business days. Delivery is via FedEx Priority, insured with signature required, typically next-day once shipped. Total timeline from design approval to delivery: 4&ndash;6 weeks.</p>

          <p><a href="/custom-engagement-rings/">Start your custom design</a></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PRICING TABLE -->
  <section class="lj-section lj-section-pad" style="background:#f9f8f6;">
    <div class="lj-container">
      <div class="lj-container--narrow" style="margin:0 auto;padding:0;">
        <div class="lj-prose">
          <h2>Engagement Ring Prices in Canada</h2>
          <p>I promised transparency and here it is. The table below shows estimated price ranges for common carat weights across three stone types in a standard solitaire setting in 14K gold.</p>

          <div class="lj-table-wrap">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Carat Weight</th>
                  <th>Lab-Grown Diamond</th>
                  <th>Natural Diamond</th>
                  <th>Moissanite</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>0.5 ct</td>
                  <td>CA$400&ndash;CA$900</td>
                  <td>CA$2,500&ndash;CA$4,500</td>
                  <td>CA$150&ndash;CA$300</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>1.0 ct</td>
                  <td>CA$800&ndash;CA$2,200</td>
                  <td>CA$6,000&ndash;CA$9,000</td>
                  <td>CA$250&ndash;CA$600</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>1.5 ct</td>
                  <td>CA$1,500&ndash;CA$3,800</td>
                  <td>CA$12,000&ndash;CA$18,000</td>
                  <td>CA$400&ndash;CA$900</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>2.0 ct</td>
                  <td>CA$2,800&ndash;CA$6,500</td>
                  <td>CA$22,000&ndash;CA$35,000</td>
                  <td>CA$600&ndash;CA$1,400</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <p>These are stone prices. Custom design, setting fabrication, and shipping are quoted separately based on the complexity of the setting. The band metal choice (14K vs 18K vs platinum 950) also affects total price.</p>
          <p><strong>Pricing subject to change. Confirm current rate at <a href="https://stan.store/luxjewels" target="_blank" rel="noopener">stan.store/luxjewels</a> before booking.</strong></p>
          <p>If you're looking for engagement rings in Canada under CA$1,000 total, moissanite in a 0.5&ndash;1ct equivalent with a standard solitaire 14K setting is absolutely achievable. If your budget is CA$2,000&ndash;CA$4,000, you're in strong territory for a 1&ndash;1.5ct lab-grown diamond with a custom setting.</p>
          <p>The key takeaway: there's no price point where I can't build something worth wearing. The stone type just changes.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ABOUT SUMAN -->
  <section class="lj-section lj-section-pad" style="background:#ffffff;">
    <div class="lj-container">
      <div class="lj-container--narrow" style="margin:0 auto;padding:0;">
        <div class="lj-prose">
          <h2>About Suman Smith</h2>
          <p>I've been working in the jewellery industry for over 20 years. I started Lux Jewels in 2007, initially as a custom design studio focused on quality over volume. The operation was small and that was intentional: I wanted to know every ring I was building and every person I was building it for.</p>
          <p>In 2015 I made a shift that most Canadian jewellers weren't ready to make. I committed fully to lab-grown diamonds as the primary stone offering. The technology had reached the point where the stones were genuinely indistinguishable from mined, the grading infrastructure was credible, and the price differential was too significant to ignore on behalf of my customers. It was an easy decision for me and a hard one to explain to the market. Now, a decade later, the market's caught up.</p>
          <p>I'm not affiliated with any mining group or stone manufacturer. I source independently and my only incentive is to match you with the right stone for your budget and your preferences. That independence matters.</p>
          <p>I do this work online. My customers are in Ontario, BC, Quebec, Alberta, the Maritimes, and across the US. I don't need a showroom to do this well. I need the right conversation, the right design process, and the right stone at a price that doesn't make you wince every time you look at your hand.</p>
          <p>That's the whole point of Lux Jewels.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
